      "it": {
        "title": "Julius Caesar & Cao Cao: The Cold Psychology Behind Extreme Pragmatism",
        "description": "Caesar and Cao Cao, heroes of different eras, reshaped history with extreme pragmatism. Uncover their psychology for modern insights.",
        "content": "We often encounter the names of heroes within the grand currents of history. Julius Caesar and Cao Cao. These two names are not merely figures from a distant past; they are mirrors reflecting the fierce realities of our own lives today – career stagnation, business crises, startup uncertainties, and even the deep-seated anxieties and depressions within our minds. The turbulent era when Caesar battled the barbarians of Gaul, shaking the foundations of the Roman Republic, and the bloody history of Cao Cao's endeavors to unify China amidst the chaos of the Three Kingdoms, resonate across millennia, echoing the pressures, the yearning for success, and the fear of failure faced by modern individuals. Their lives are not just narratives of power struggles; they are continuous, intricate psychological games of ambition, survival instincts, and forging paths through harsh realities.\n\nThis blog post aims to delve deeply into the cold psychology hidden behind the 'extreme pragmatism' of Julius Caesar and Cao Cao. We will explore how they, amidst the chaos and adversity of their respective eras, not only survived but made decisions that overturned the status quo and reshaped history. This is not merely an admiration of great strategists from the past. It is a journey to provide practical approaches for goal achievement and a profound understanding of human psychology, essential for us navigating modern society. Caesar's declaration, 'The die is cast,' and Cao Cao's strategy, 'Make the enemy suspect me,' are not mere acts of courage or wisdom but the results of calculated risk-taking and insights that pierced the opponent's psyche. Through their lives and choices, we will gain powerful insights applicable to our own contemporary problems.\n\n### Strategists Across Time: A Meeting of Caesar and Cao Cao\n\nThough operating in different eras and cultural contexts, Caesar and Cao Cao seized power and moved history in remarkably similar ways. Caesar, amidst the extreme political corruption and power struggles of the late Roman Republic, gradually expanded his influence based on military success and popular appeal. His victories in the Gallic Wars were not just territorial expansions but the epitome of a dual strategy: promising prosperity and stability to Roman citizens while posing a formidable military threat to his rivals. He instilled 'personal' loyalty in his soldiers, a crucial factor that made them follow him without hesitation when he crossed the Rubicon. Cao Cao, in the chaos of the late Han Dynasty, set a realistic goal of 'unifying the realm under the Emperor's banner,' leveraging his outstanding military prowess. While numerous heroes sought to establish their own kingdoms, he shrewdly used the authority of the central government while emphasizing legitimacy. His ruthless pragmatism, exemplified by incidents like the 'killing of the innocent villagers' (生勣), was used to eliminate rivals and solidify his position. This can be seen as a textbook case of extreme pragmatism: 'achieving the goal by any means necessary.'\n\n### The Tightrope Walk of Ambition and Reality: A Cold Psychological Analysis\n\nBoth figures harbored immense ambitions, but their realization was marked by extreme coldness and pragmatism. Caesar, to achieve his ambitions, boldly disregarded Roman traditions and laws. His famous words, 'Alea iacta est' (The die is cast), signify not only his decisiveness to never look back once a decision was made but also a conclusion he could draw because he had already manipulated the situation to his advantage. He was adept at understanding the public's psychology, skillfully portraying himself as a hero and savior. His 'Commentaries' were not mere war records but meticulously crafted political propaganda to publicize his achievements and gain popular support. Cao Cao was similar. He harbored the grand ambition of 'ruling all under heaven,' but his attitude was often, 'I don't care if people see me as a villain, as long as I achieve my goal.' Regardless of his image, he focused solely on achieving his objectives. He constantly analyzed his rivals' psyches, exploited their weaknesses, and sometimes employed deception and trickery to attain his aims. This was the result of a highly realistic psychological warfare, maximizing the inherent selfishness and survival instincts within human nature.\n\n### Seizing Opportunity Amidst Crisis: Exceptional Crisis Management\n\nCaesar and Cao Cao both excelled at turning chaos and crisis into opportunity. Caesar accurately perceived the corruption of the Roman Republic and the discontent of its citizens. He militarized his legions, used his personal fortune to bribe soldiers, and gained popularity by providing 'bread and circuses' to the masses. Whenever his political opponents tried to eliminate him, he used these attempts as opportunities for decisive counterattacks. His success in Gaul brought him immense wealth and a loyal army, which eventually became the foundation for his return to Rome and seizure of power. Cao Cao, too, leveraged the chaos following Dong Zhuo's tyranny, when the Emperor became a puppet. He raised an army and expanded his influence under the banner of 'suppressing the Yellow Turbans.' He proved his military capabilities through numerous victories and, simultaneously, appointed civil officials to build administrative capacity. Furthermore, he fostered divisions among his rivals and sometimes formed and then betrayed alliances, prioritizing his own survival and power expansion amidst complex political situations. Their crisis management skills were not mere luck but the result of thorough situational analysis, cold judgment, and bold decision-making.\n\n### Practical Guidance for Modern Individuals\n\nFrom the lives of Caesar and Cao Cao, we can glean valuable lessons applicable to ourselves navigating modern society. Their extreme pragmatism and cold psychology offer significant insights for our career development, business strategies, and mental health management today.\n\n1. Define your goals clearly and adopt a realistic approach that utilizes all available means. Avoid getting bogged down in ideals or principles; instead, analyze the situation coldly to find the most effective path.\n2. Accurately assess your strengths and weaknesses, and formulate strategies based on this understanding. Just as Caesar utilized his military prowess and Cao Cao his political acumen, maximizing your core competencies is crucial.\n3. Understand the psychology of others and use it strategically. Grasping the mindset of rivals, colleagues, and even customers is essential for building successful relationships and negotiations.\n4. Do not fear crises; instead, cultivate a counter-intuitive mindset to turn them into opportunities. Remember that new possibilities lie hidden within every problem, and dare to challenge them boldly.\n\nThe stories of Caesar and Cao Cao are not just tales from the past. Their wisdom and strategies remain relevant today, offering valuable insights to overcome our challenges and build a better future. Their sagas remind us to face reality, judge coldly, and act boldly.\n\n[If you wish to discuss your problems directly with this giant, start a 1:1 chat room here](/giant/julius-caesar)"
      },
      "pt": {
        "title": "Julius Caesar & Cao Cao: The Cold Psychology Behind Extreme Pragmatism",
        "description": "Caesar and Cao Cao, heroes of different eras, reshaped history with extreme pragmatism. Uncover their psychology for modern insights.",
        "content": "We often encounter the names of heroes within the grand currents of history. Julius Caesar and Cao Cao. These two names are not merely figures from a distant past; they are mirrors reflecting the fierce realities of our own lives today – career stagnation, business crises, startup uncertainties, and even the deep-seated anxieties and depressions within our minds. The turbulent era when Caesar battled the barbarians of Gaul, shaking the foundations of the Roman Republic, and the bloody history of Cao Cao's endeavors to unify China amidst the chaos of the Three Kingdoms, resonate across millennia, echoing the pressures, the yearning for success, and the fear of failure faced by modern individuals. Their lives are not just narratives of power struggles; they are continuous, intricate psychological games of ambition, survival instincts, and forging paths through harsh realities.\n\nThis blog post aims to delve deeply into the cold psychology hidden behind the 'extreme pragmatism' of Julius Caesar and Cao Cao. We will explore how they, amidst the chaos and adversity of their respective eras, not only survived but made decisions that overturned the status quo and reshaped history. This is not merely an admiration of great strategists from the past. It is a journey to provide practical approaches for goal achievement and a profound understanding of human psychology, essential for us navigating modern society. Caesar's declaration, 'The die is cast,' and Cao Cao's strategy, 'Make the enemy suspect me,' are not mere acts of courage or wisdom but the results of calculated risk-taking and insights that pierced the opponent's psyche. Through their lives and choices, we will gain powerful insights applicable to our own contemporary problems.\n\n### Strategists Across Time: A Meeting of Caesar and Cao Cao\n\nThough operating in different eras and cultural contexts, Caesar and Cao Cao seized power and moved history in remarkably similar ways. Caesar, amidst the